div.p:
I find no ſuch thing in the holy Martyr. 'Tis true, I read theſe words, By which Food (chang'd in our Bodies, 
                           〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                        ) our Blood and Fleſh are nouriſhed. What then? Bread and Wine taken out of the Sacrament, nouriſh, according to this Paſſage, Fleſh and Blood, which all the World will allow of. And I ſhall believe St. Juſtin ſays no more, till you can prove it from the Saint's own Teſtimonie. But why do I ſay Teſtimonie, when the Paſſage you cite, is nothing but a bare Parentheſis? I could heap up a great many ſuch weakneſſes, collected out of your Diſcourſe, if the World were not already too much troubled with ſuch trivial Reflections. I'll take liberty to add one more conſiderable, viz. If natural digeſtion can change Bread and Wine into the proper Subſtance of our Bodies, how eaſy will it be to Nature's Author, to change one thing into another, Bread into the Body of Chriſt? Nor can any moderate Man imagin any thing leſs, when the Devil himſelf tempted Chriſt to change one Subſtance into another, Stones into Bread, as a Strategem to find out, whether he was God.
